Entities have two possible representations, and you must choose the one
that you want.  The small representation (sment.h) uses only one word to
store entities.  The disadvantage is that pointers are stored in 26 bits,
and so have a limited range.  The large representation (lgent.h) uses
a structure to represent an entity.  It uses full 32 bit pointers, but 
entities are five bytes long.

In the small representation, pointers in entities are stored as offsets 
from heap_base.  Word pointers are stored without their rightmost 2 bits, 
which are presumed to be 0.

In both representations, each entity has a tag and a value, except for
strings, which have more fields (see below). Suppose e is an entity.
To obtain the tag of e, use TAG(e). To obtain the value, use one of
the VAL macros in sment.h or lgent.h.  For example, to obtain the
integer value, use IVAL(e).  To construct an entity, use one of the
ENT macros in sment.h or lgent.h.

The following kinds of entities are available.  Note that these 
values are the underlying representations of the entities; 
entities that can cast back and forth have the same representation.


Tag		Discussion
---		----------
NOREF_TAG	Used to store integers and quantities represented by
		integers, such as booleans.  INT_TAG is the same, only
		used in the code for types Integer and Natural.
		Booleans are stored with 0 = false, 1 = true.  Hermit
		has value 0.  The list nil has the same representation
		as the hermit.

		NOREF_TAG is also used for wrapped hermits.  See WRAP_TAG.


GLOBAL_TAG	The value field holds an index k in ent_names of the record
		for an identifier x.  This kind of entity is found only in
		a pair, where the second entity in the pair is the type of
		this global id.  (That is, if entity p[0] has
		tag GLOBAL_TAG, the then entity p[1] has tag TYPE_TAG.)


GLOBAL_INDIRECT_TAG	The value is a pointer to a pair (val,type)
			of entities, where val is the value of this
			entity, and type is its type.  GLOBAL_TAG 
			entities are always accessed though GLOBAL_INDIRECT_TAG
			entities, so that lazy evaluation can replace
			the value.  Note that val might have tag GLOBAL_TAG,
			and might have another tag.


INDIRECT_TAG	The value is a pointer to the entity. Used for indirection
		to a lazy value, so that memoizations are visible to all
		copies.


LAZY_LIST_TAG   The value is a pointer to an up-control node that represents
		the expression that computes the stream of this list.
		Failing with this control causes the generator to start, and
		to get the next value in the list.


LAZY_TAG	The value is a pointer to a down-control node that represents
		the expression that computes this value. To evaluate, start
		with this control.


LAZY_PRIM_TAG	This entity is the value of a computation that has timed-out,
		or is a lazy primitive.  The value is a pointer to a triple
		of entities (kind,val1,val2), where kind is the kind of
		lazy primitive, and (val1,val2) are its parameters.


FAIL_TAG	This is the result of a failed lazy computation.
		The value is the exception number.


BIGNEGINT_TAG,BIGPOSINT_TAG
		The value is a pointer to a binary chunk of memory giving the
		absolute value of an integer.  BIGNEGINT_TAG is used 
		for a negative integer, and BIGPOSINT_TAG is used for
		a positive integer.  These tags are only used for 
		truly large integers -- integers with small absolute
		value are always represented using NOREF_TAG.

		A binary chunk is stored as follows.  The first two bytes
		of the chunk are the header, and hold two mark 
		bits and 14 bits that tell the length of the chunk, in 
		bytes.  The length stored is the number of data bytes, 
		and does not count the header itself.
		The remaining bytes consist of the data, and are thought 
		of as an array of intcells.  (The intcells are
		two bytes each.)

		There is a special case where the size stored in the
		header is 0x3fff.  In that case, the chunk is a very 
		large one.  The next four bytes after the two-byte
		header hold the size of the chunk, in bytes.  As before
		the size does not count the two byte header or the 
		four bytes after that.  The data comes after that.

STRING_TAG	The value is a pointer to a binary chunk, as described
		under BIGPOSINT_TAG, above.  In this case, the content
		is thought of as an array of bytes.
			   
CSTR_TAG	The value is a pointer to a null-terminated string.
		The string is in the string hash table, so two CSTR_TAG
		values are the same string just when their pointers
		are the same.

SMALL_REAL_TAG	The value is a pointer to a double precision floating
		point value.


LARGE_REAL_TAG	The value is a pointer to a pair (man,ex) consisting of
		the mantissa and exponent to base INT_BASE =
	        2^{BITS_IN_INTCELL}.


RATIONAL_TAG	The value is a pair (a,b), representing the rational value
		a/b.


WRAP_TAG	This is an entity wrapped with a tag that is either a 
		type or an integer. The value is a pointer to a pair 
		of entities (tag,val), where val is the value and
		tag is the tag.  

		In the case where val is the hermit and tag is an integer,
		a NOREF_TAG is used instead of a WRAP_TAG, and the 
		value is the tag.


QWRAP0_TAG, QWRAP1_TAG, QWRAP2_TAG, QWRAP3_TAG
		These are shorthands for wraps.  QWRAPx_TAG with value
		e is the same as WRAP_TAG with value (x,e).  


FILE_TAG	The value is a pointer to a file entity, describing an
		input or output file or a font.


FUNCTION_TAG	The value is a pointer to a continuation for the function.


PAIR_TAG, TRIPLE_TAG, QUAD_TAG
	  	These are used for lists and products.  The value is a 
		pointer to a block of n entities, consisting of the first 
		n-1 entities in the list or product followed by a single
		entity that is the remainder of the list or product.  The
		tag indicates the value of n.  PAIR_TAG indicates
		that n = 2, TRIPLE_TAG that n = 3 and QUAD_TAG that
		n = 4.  A PAIR_TAG entity is thus a cons pair, holding
		a pointer to a pair (h,t) of the head and tail of the list.


ARRAY_TAG	An ARRAY_TAG entity points to a header that describes
		a random-access list or an integer.  The header holds
		two or more values, the first being the length of the
		list (or of the front part of the list),
		the second being the body of the list.  The length
		field must always have tag INT_TAG.  The tag of the
		body value tells what kind of list is being stored.

		Tag BOX_TAG:

		  There are only two header entries, (l,b).  (b has
		  tag BOX_TAG.)  This list is a list of nonshared
		  boxes b, b+1, ..., b+l-1.

		Tag PLACE_TAG:

		  There are four entries in the header, (l,p,r,a).
		  (p has tag PLACE_TAG.) This list is a list of
		  shared boxes p, p+1, ..., p+l-1 followed by list r.

		  Field a is used for garbage collection.  It is an array
		  of which p, p+1, ..., p+l-1 is a subarray.
		  That array is marked rather than this one.  If a is nil,
		  then this is not a subarray of any other array.

		Tag INDIRECT_TAG:

		  There are four entries in the header, (l,s,r,k).  This
		  list is a list of entities stored at consecutive
		  addresses s, s+1, ..., s+l-1, followed by list r.
		  Field k is used for garbage collection.  It is the
		  number of entries beyond the end of this array that
		  need to be marked when this array is marked.

		Tag STRING_TAG

		  The value is a quadruple of entities (l,s,r,k).  This
		  list consists of the sublist of string s of length l
		  beginning k bytes beyond the beginning of s, followed
		  by list r.

		Tag ENTITY_TOP_TAG:

		  There are three entries in the header, (l,s,r).  This array
		  is the concatenation of the arrays stored at s, s+1, ...,
		  s+l-1, followed by list r.  Each the arrays stored at
		  s, s+1, ... must have tag ARRAY_TAG,
		  and each of those arrays must have kind INDIRECT_TAG
		  or PLACE_TAG.

                  Each of those arrays must have a follower field of nil.
		  All but the last of s, s+1, ..., s+l-1 must have
                  size exactly ENT_BLOCK_GRAB_SIZE.

APPEND_TAG	This is the concatenation of two lists.  The value is a
		pointer to a pair of entities (l,r), where this list is
		l ++ r.

		APPEND_TAGs are only used in special circumstances, to
		create a lazy append.  The left-subtree of an
		APPEND_TAG has a list structure that is not lazy, although
		the members of the list can be lazy.

TREE_TAG	Operator ++ uses a list data structure due to Okasaki.  A
		list is represented as a multi-way branching tree, where
		the list consists of a preorder traversal of the tree.
		Each node of the tree contains a value, except nodes that
		are *vacant*.  Vacant nodes are skipped in the preorder
		traversal.

		The children of a tree node are stored, left-to-right,
		as a queue.  The queue, in turn, is stored by four
		quantities: (f,m,r,n) where f and r are lists, m is
		the length of f and n is the length of r.  The queue
		contains f followed by the reversal of r.

		A tree node therefore has five values associated with it:
		(key,f,m,r,n).  If key is NOTHING, then the node is
		vacant.  The implementation of Okasaki's algorithm is
		in file append.c.


BOX_TAG		The value is a box number.


PLACE_TAG	The value is the address of the place.


DEMON_TAG	This kind of entity only occurs as the content of a box
		or place.  The value is the address of a pair (v,l) 
		where v is the content of the box or place (or NOTHING
		for an empty box or place) and l is a list of pairs
		of the form (bx,f) where bx is a box or place that
		contains a boolean value and f is a function.  

		Suppose that b is a box that has value DEMON_TAG(old,l),
		and that l contains pair (x,f).  If assign! b := new.
		is executed, the following happens.
		   Box x is checked. If x contains true, then no event
		   is done.  If x contains false or is empty, then 
		      1. x is assigned true.
		      2. f(b,old,new) is computed.  It must return ().
		      3. x is assigned false.
		This processing is done for each pair (x,f) in l.


TYPE_TAG	A type.  The value is a pointer to the type.


RELOCATE_TAG	Used for relocating entities during garbage collection.
		The value is a pointer to the cell where this entity
		has moved to.
=============================================================================
